<feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><title>Nasser's Blog</title><link href="http://www.nass3r.com/" rel="alternate"></link><link href="http://www.nass3r.com/feeds/programming.atom.xml" rel="self"></link><id>http://www.nass3r.com/</id><updated>2012-12-04T21:48:00+01:00</updated><entry><title>MathÂ puzzle</title><link href="http://www.nass3r.com/math-puzzle-4.html" rel="alternate"></link><updated>2012-12-04T21:48:00+01:00</updated><author><name>nasser</name></author><id>tag:www.nass3r.com,2012-12-04:math-puzzle-4.html</id><summary type="html">&lt;p&gt;Yesterday, I was asked to solve a math puzzle that goes like&amp;nbsp;this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You have a 3x3 matrix where you have to fill it with&amp;nbsp;the numbers 1-9,
as&amp;nbsp;follows:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;table border="1" class="docutils"&gt;
&lt;colgroup&gt;
&lt;col width="33%" /&gt;
&lt;col width="33%" /&gt;
&lt;col width="33%" /&gt;
&lt;/colgroup&gt;
&lt;tbody valign="top"&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;N1&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;N2&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;N3&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;N4&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;N5&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;N6&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;N7&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;N8&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td&gt;N9&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Where:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;N1 + N4 =&amp;nbsp;N7,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;N2 + N5 =&amp;nbsp;N8,&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;N3 + N6 =&amp;nbsp;N9&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;and no&amp;nbsp;repetition&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;allowed!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So I spent sometime trying to solve it. Then I wrote a little Python
script to help me solve it, but it too didn&amp;#8217;t work. It was a bit
frustrating, to be honest. So I thought about it differently. We know
that an Even number + another Even number will yield an Even number. and
an Odd number + an Odd number will also yield an Even number. The only
case where we can get an Odd number is when we add an Even number with
an Odd number. Let me state these in a clear&amp;nbsp;way.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;O + O =&amp;nbsp;E&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;E + E =&amp;nbsp;E&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;O + E =&amp;nbsp;O&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So I counted the Odds and Evens in the list, which&amp;nbsp;are:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class="simple"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;1 &amp;#8212;&amp;nbsp;O&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;2 &amp;#8212;&amp;nbsp;E&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;3 &amp;#8212;&amp;nbsp;O&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;4 &amp;#8212;&amp;nbsp;E&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;5 &amp;#8212;&amp;nbsp;O&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;6 &amp;#8212;&amp;nbsp;E&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;7 &amp;#8212;&amp;nbsp;O&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;8 &amp;#8212;&amp;nbsp;E&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;9 &amp;#8212;&amp;nbsp;O&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;5 Odds&lt;/strong&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;4&amp;nbsp;Evens&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, no matter how you arrange the first two rows of the matrix, you
can&amp;#8217;t come up with a formation that will satisfy these constraints&amp;nbsp;:)&lt;/p&gt;
